caption: Terrific food, great service, good outdoor dining space
No long winded review. The food speaks for itself.

Hooray for indoor dining!  Delicious margarita to start, followed by a tasty pan seared salmon and warm chocolate brioche for dessert.  Everything was yummy, but service was very slow and inattentive.

Love this restaurant! It never disappoints ever. It is consistently yummy. It’s specialty menus during the pandemic have made those days special even when it’s difficult. The regular menu is amazing as well. Their food is always cooked so well with tons of flavor. I have never had a bad meal. That egg in the Cobb salad is genius. Great local restaurant with super friendly staff. The food is just cooked very well with the right seasoning, amazing sauces and great flavor.
Great outdoor seating in the sun during winter. Food and service both exceptional and a nice varied menu for brunch.
One of the “go tos” for brunch in the neighborhood. Brunch is always delicious. They have THE best pancakes!
Such a good brunch spot - loved the chef’s omelette, pancakes, and Bloody Mary! They have outdoor seating with heat lamps, the food was really excellent, and service was great ❤️
Great, spacious outdoor seating and a delicious menu. Lovely staff!
A good place for dinner and drinks. I wish there were more vegetarian and vegan options. Overall, a good place to spend your outdoor meals with a group.

The restaurant was a nice looking place.  It was bigger than I thought.  They offer full or half portions.  I had the roasted chicken which was delicious.  For dessert I had the caramel ice cream with whipped cream.  The service was great.  My only complaint was it's a bit pricey.

Cozy venue with beautiful window seating - manicured, up-scale American venue. The server Conner was great - very knowledgable and professional, made great recommendations and was attentive, humorous.  This spot makes a GREAT steak, and a GREAT old-fashioned (also a great pairing). Potato/leek soup with bleu cheese was surprisingly good. I'd come back here for sure.  There is a special Thanksgiving menu as well for those in town that day.

Let me lead with it was my tiny wedding brunch and I'm a picky eater, so high expectations!  All of which were met. Temperature checks, thank you! It was extremely clean, all the staff were cautious and professional. Masks! Just felt so comfortable in these wild times. The food itself was plentiful, and well made- I couldnt finish my bacon. Which was DELICIOUS. and the drinks were great! Burton went above and beyond, and answered all my MANY questions beforehand. Absolutely going back!

Had a great opportunity to try this place on a weekend trip in NYC. We decided on brunch and walked to the restaurant Saturday mornings , very impressed at adapting to the COVID regulations. We were able to sit in the front patio and had everything delivered very fast. Service was phenomenal. Food was great too, highly recommend.

The food and the prices were very good and they have a lot of tables outside. Windows open on the inside space and they are strict with the desinfecting of tables. We had an excellent experience there.
Stellar good, menu options and service. Everything was delicious!
Very comfortable outdoor seating area and upscale fare on the menu. The price point is slightly higher than average, but well worth it.

I order a beer and they gave me a different beer from the same brewery.   They were gracious enough to remove it from my bill going back to the good service part.

I thought the flavors paired nicely with the food without being overwhelming and taking over the flavor. Our service was top notch and the bartender seemed to know all of her patrons - lovely to watch. I had the pork chop and my friend the half a chicken both were excellent. The food at the Stone Park Cafe is excellent but once I had an issue with a couple of bad clams but probably that is something that happens with clams in the summer.  The menu is a bit overpriced, but all and all a definite cut above other places. 2 issues: improve your summer A/C, and play better music and not so loud. For a sophisticated restaurant can you please play jazz or Frank Sinatra or the like, instead if the occasional bad pop or elevator music which is in your face (ear)if you happen to sit near one of the speakers.

Wish I could leave zero stars. We were emailing with the owner Josh about hosting our wedding ceremony and reception here. He offered us a time to view the space but unfortunately it didn't work with our schedules so we asked if there was a day we could swing by a little later. Out of nowhere our emails bounced back. I called and was given Josh's personal email address by one of the employees. I reached out, called again and was promised he would get back to me. He never did! We later realized he blocked our email addresses. DISGUSTING WAY TO TREAT CUSTOMERS! I'm just happy we didn't pay a deposit and get locked in with nasty owner.

I came here with colleagues to celebrate someone’s retirement. We dined in a private room where we set the playlist on the sound system for our party. The place was comfortable and intimate with soft lighting and and a small outdoor courtyard off of the room. The staff were attentive and friendly. We started with a cheese and cracker mingle with glasses of Krava. We had a choice of appetizer, main course, and dessert. Bread and butter was provided at each table and then mini platters of a type of mini pizza on a thin cracker thin dough. My spring salad was made of watercress, steamed soft carrots, asparagus and radishes. It had tiny dressing dollops around the edge of the salad. It was surprisingly good. My main course was a delight and the mango salsa dressing was tasty. I was impressed at how well the flavors complimented each other. It was my first time having creme brûlée and now the bar is set because it was delicious.
I loved service, good food and variety in menu. This place is busy on Sunday, you need to make reservation, but it worse it. I am doing keto and this salad was a good option.
well worth the wait.  Excellent food.

Love coming to the Stone Park Cafe on summer evenings. There's always enough shade and given that it's just across from the park, a little bit of a breeze. Makes the excellent food taste even better!

STYLISH SMALL-BALL EATERY (Warning: sports metaphors ahead) Stone Park is the adult in the Park Slope restaurant scene and practices small-ball, which is no criticism. It’s kitchen and front-of-house staff are not swinging for home runs night after night but instead successfully seek high averages on variety, food quality and presentation, hospitality, cocktails and comfortable innovation. Theatrics are few and the pleasures satisfying. Though primarily a neighborhood place, we travel two or three miles several times a month for the fried chicken, frisée salad and soups. the Four Roses Manhattan does Brooklyn proud, and the gentle variations on G&Ts are distinctive. Seats in the back are two steps down from the bar level and quieter.  LOO REVIEW: Two snug, tidy and under lit WCs that serve all genders and come with half-glass doors so frosted and shaded diners must rattle the knob to determine if either is occupied. To avoid over share moments, double check the interior latches.

One sees parents with strollers or couples just walking by. So many people out and about, each one with a story of their own, while you sit sipping coffee and mesmerising as life passes you by. I am sure the photos I share will speak more than the words. Visiting the cafe for the first hand experience will be worth it.

We just left this restaurant. Its August 31, 2018 at 1:30. My husband and I sat there for 15 minutes as various servers walked back and forth past our table without so much as an acknowledgment.  We truly felt invisible.  Perhaps it was that we were different from most people in the restaurant (meaning brown). Perhaps it was a general lack of professionalism to go along with a mediocre menu? We decided to get up and leave rather than be disrespected in a restuarant that was clearly not busy. If you want to support a restaurant that makes others feel invisible then this is your place. Otherwise take your business and dollars elsewhere, as we just did. There are plenty of other fabulous restaurants in the area that would love to have your business, no matter who you are and what you look like. I will be sure to spread the word far and wide! Keep up the good work folks.... ✌️✌️✌️✌️

We hosted my sister's brunch Baby Shower at The Stone Park Café in March. Working with Liz and her day of event team was a seamless and lovely experience that went above and beyond our expectations. My sister chose this location and she chose right! Liz was constantly and consistently available to us during the planning process. She proactively checked in with my Mother and I in the weeks leading up to the shower. She was available by email, phone, and text message. Which made checking in while doing last minute shower preparation much easier. Liz also offered us the option (which we took advantage of) to drop off our shower decorations with instructions on set-up the day before the shower. We left post its on where we'd like the different decorations set up because there wasn't an event happening in the space that day. If there is, you can leave a diagram and instructions for Liz and her team. The team also was understanding of our desired table arrangements.  When we arrived about an hour before the start of the Shower, there was very little for us to do besides look everything over and enjoy! They know how to set up their space to perfection. It was like a mini-wedding. Starting with the personalized chalkboard which was a nice touch and also a smart way to guide people to the event space. It's not hard to find but it's always nice for guests. The space is classy, classic, and fun with the exposed brick, candles everywhere (!!) and cocktail tables set up near the front with the gift table. The bar was so cool. No detail was overlooked with the bar menu matching our decorations, specially printed for our group with "Oh Baby!" written on top. The food menus were personalized to my sister as well. The table settings were stunning and matched our blue color theme. All of this was done by The Stone Park Café team. Working with them was like having a personal event coordinator/party planner. No attention to detail was sparred.  When we arrived, Liz introduced us to the day of event staff who were professional and friendly. I had a few requests during the event (move a cocktail table for games into the main dining room for example) and it was done quickly and quietly with a smile. Liz and her team were so great and kept us on a timeline (our event was 3 hours) that allowed for a nice flow of almost a "cocktail hour", brunch, playing games, and allowing people to mingle and spend time with each other. Including my Mother and I. Which isn't always the case when hosting a shower!  You cannot do better than the Stone Park Café. On top of that, it's conveniently located in Brooklyn (our group came from all 5 boroughs and Westchester) and the food was outstanding. Each guest was greeted by a team member personally, their coats taken, offered a drink, and welcomed into the event. It was delightful. And allowed our guests and my Mother and I to focus on my sister and our guests.  Choosing your menu will be the biggest challenge - too many good things to choose from. We had a menu of 2 salad choices, 3 brunch choices, and cake for dessert. Their cakes are delicious and can be designed as you wish. They brought the cake into the space for my sister to cut. Since we had a brunch, coffee and tea were self serve at the bar all afternoon. An awesome touch! The bar was options included a specialty cocktail, Bellini, mimosa, beer, wine, soda, and water. The bar itself was very cool and provided another area across from our game set ups for people to relax and spend time with each other. They even had outside set up with cocktail tables and candles ready to go. An incredibly lovely touch. It was picture perfect.  We can't say enough about the location, food, team, and our experience at The Stone Park Café. We look forward to working with Liz and her team in the future. We can't recommend them highly enough.  Thank you to the team at Stone Park Café! Paula and Janice Caruselle

One of the nicest spots in Park Slope.  Great food, a little more polished than most places, but not pretentious.

Came here years ago when it was new to the neighborhood and I remembered the food being good. Revisited lately due to a friend's interest in trying it and I'm stumped as to why I stopped coming here. I mean, it's likely due to the fact that there are so many good restaurants in New York. There are a plethora of dining options, but Stone Park Cafe has maintained, if not improved, the quality of their dishes over the years. And having tried so many restaurants in the area, I can safely say that their food tops many others.  My friends and I came for a late brunch (2pm) to avoid the crowds and wait. They stop serving brunch at 3pm, so it's just enough time to get our orders in and dine in a quieter atmosphere. Decor is clean and modern, yet comfortable. Ambience was bright and casual for brunch. We ordered the Eggs Any Style, Eggs Benedict, Buttermilk Pancakes, and Shrimp and Grits. All of the dishes were prepared well and everything was tasty. Service was friendly, prompt, and accommodating. A great brunch date! I will be back!

I can't speak to the service or quality at dinner, but we came for brunch and it was a really disappointing experience. It's an OK place. Quaint atmosphere with service that was well paced and sufficiently available without being intrusive. Though the waitresses should be more familiar with the menu and drink lists than mine was.  We stopped in for lunch. They have a decent wine and beer selection. The server pointed us to the three course prix fixe lunch menu. Three courses is a pretty big lunch, but you can order al la carte from that menu as well.  I chose to order from the standard lunch menu and got the crispy fish tacos with shaved fennel salad. The fish looked like the fish sticks I had as a kid, but tasted slightly better because they were not greasy and slightly worse because they were over breaded, over cooked, and bland. The tortillas and red cabbage slaw were unseasoned and bland too. The aioli tasted nice, though for a taco I would have liked a condiment option with some spice. The shaved fennel salad was mostly arugula, with the tiniest bit of fennel shaved into it and  dressed with a vinaigrette. It may have been unfair to refer to it as a shaved fennel salad. The dressing was the best part of the plate, but there was too little of it.  In sum, it was an overly expensive lunch that was disappointing in almost every aspect.

Our party of 4 came in one Sunday afternoon a little before 11, right after we had just run a 5k race in Prospect Park. The wait for a table was about 20 minutes, or we had the option of sitting by the bar, which was no wait. We opted for the latter because again, we had just run a 5k and we (and when I say we, I mean I) were hangry.  Now I normally don't order omelettes because I feel like I can make pretty good omelettes at home, and they're not usually worth the price tag. And that is probably the main reason I go out to eat - to try foods that I couldn't make (well) at home. However, there was nothing else on the menu that really appealed to me, so the omelette is what I ended up getting. You can choose 4 ingredients, so I went with bacon, tomatoes, spinach, and pepper jack - can't forget the cheese. This came with a side of home fries and toast.  This could be the best omelette I have ever eaten - way better than anything I could ever make at home. The eggs are perfect - not just perfectly cooked, but just perfect. They look so pretty! Plus the home fries, which most other places use as a filler, were pretty good here. So I looked at it more as a complement to the omelette, as opposed to something to make you full because the omelette might not be enough.  I only wish Stone Park Cafe was closer to where I lived. Then I could have their omelettes whenever I wanted.  TIP - ask for the Salamander hot sauce. This might be my new fave.
